            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>Case: A High-Performing Creative That Almost Cost Me $20,000</h2>
<p>Last Wednesday night, I received a message from Lao Zhou, an independent fashion site seller: "My ad ran for 20 days, spent $18,000, got only 7 conversions, and my CPC is only $0.30. Can this creative be saved?"</p>
<p>I asked him to send screenshots of his backend data. After reviewing it, I had a clear picture—this was a classic case of an ad that "runs" but doesn't "sell."</p>
<p>Where was the problem?</p>
<p>His CTR was 4.2%, well above industry average, and his CPC looked great. But digging deeper into user behavior: average page dwell time was 38 seconds, add-to-cart rate was only 1.1%, and cart abandonment rate hit 78%. Users clicked in but left without purchasing—they were attracted by the creative but had no real buying intent.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>"Running performance" and "selling performance" are two independent metrics, yet many optimizers only monitor the former and end up wasting money.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>How to Identify Whether Your Creative "Runs" or "Sells"</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Break Down the Data Chain, Don't Just Watch Front-End Metrics</h3>
<p>When reviewing creatives, many people only look at CPM, CPC, and CTR. These are fundamentals, but they only tell you "whether users are willing to click in"—not "whether they're willing to pay."</p>
<p>What you really need to compare are two sets of data:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Dimension</th>
<th>"Runs" Creative</th>
<th>"Sells" Creative</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>CTR</td>
<td>High (≥2%)</td>
<td>Moderate (0.8-1.5%)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Dwell Time</td>
<td>Short (15-30s)</td>
<td>Long (≥60s)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Add-to-Cart Rate</td>
<td>Low (&lt;2%)</td>
<td>High (≥5%)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>CPA</td>
<td>Low but low volume</td>
<td>Reasonable and stable</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Back to Lao Zhou's case: his CTR of 4.2% qualified as "runs." But the 1.1% add-to-cart rate and 78% cart abandonment meant the people coming in weren't genuine buyers—they were either lured by overhyped claims or had misaligned price expectations.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Track User Intent, Don't Just Watch ROI Numbers</h3>
<p>Sometimes ROI looks acceptable, but after detailed analysis, you realize natural traffic is carrying the numbers while paid traffic is actually losing money.</p>
<p>I recommend enabling <strong>attribution window comparison</strong> in Meta Ads Manager: compare "7-day click attribution" and "1-day conversion attribution" side by side. If 7-day conversions far exceed 1-day, it means your landing page or product is delaying conversions—these creatives need landing page optimization, not blind scaling.</p>
<hr />
<h2>How to Handle Creatives That "Run" But Don't "Sell"</h2>
<h3>Judgment: Pause First, Then Filter—Don't Rush to Optimize</h3>
<p>Not every creative is worth saving. If the core selling point has fundamental flaws (overpromising, targeting misalignment), continuing to optimize is a waste of time.</p>
<p><strong>Recommended filtering criteria:</strong><br />
- Impressions ≥5,000, CTR normal, but zero conversions for ≥3 consecutive days → Pause<br />
- Impressions ≥5,000, CTR normal, add-to-cart rate &lt;1.5% → Recheck landing page alignment<br />
- Impressions &lt;3,000, no conversions → Continue monitoring; sample size insufficient</p>
<h3>Action: Tiered Management with a Creative Lifecycle Table</h3>
<p>I categorize creatives into three tiers:</p>
<p><strong>1. Scaling Potential Group</strong><br />
CTR ≥1.5x industry average, add-to-cart rate ≥3%—these creatives enter the scaling track while continuously producing new versions for A/B testing to prevent decay after peak performance.</p>
<p><strong>2. Observation Group</strong><br />
CTR normal but add-to-cart rate low (1-3%)—the selling point is likely fine, but the presentation isn't compelling enough to drive purchase intent. Focus on optimizing CTA copy and product display angles, with a 7-10 day testing window.</p>
<p><strong>3. Retirement Zone</strong><br />
CTR normal but add-to-cart rate &lt;1%, or low CTR itself. The former indicates a mismatch between product and user needs; the latter means the creative simply isn't attractive. Shut down both categories and reallocate budget to the first two groups.</p>
<p>Lao Zhou's creative fell into the third category. I advised him to pause it immediately and redirect 30% of the remaining $18,000 budget into a new ad group for testing.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Results: Two-Week Data Review</h2>
<p>After applying this framework, Lao Zhou's new test creative spent approximately $6,000 in the first week, generating 13 conversions at a CPA of $46—82% lower than the previous "runs but doesn't sell" creative ($257 CPA).</p>
<p>More importantly, he ran a complete review of historical data and discovered that only 23% of the creatives his team produced over the past three months were truly "selling" creatives. The remaining 77% were all "running" types—impressive-looking metrics but burning money without retaining customers.</p>
<hr />
<h2>One-Line Takeaway</h2>
<p>Running performance is the threshold; selling performance is the goal. Next time you review your creatives, add add-to-cart rate and checkout data to your core dashboard. Stop letting CTR fool you.</p>
